00:02:10.240 --> 00:02:15.690
So before we begin with talking
about crowd source mapping Curtis

00:02:15.690 --> 00:02:19.490
and I had a little
conversation and we wanted

00:02:19.490 --> 00:02:26.830
to establish some historical and
cultural context for this event.

00:02:26.830 --> 00:02:32.520
Why is it relevant to
crowd source North Korea.

00:02:32.520 --> 00:02:36.000
Why should that happen, what is
important about that practice?

00:02:42.060 --> 00:02:46.140
So what I want to do is highlight
a few things concerning the history

00:02:46.140 --> 00:02:50.820
and culture of the Korean
Peninsula in North Korea.

00:02:51.940 --> 00:03:02.580 position:56%
So premodern Korea had
isolationist policies often referred

00:03:02.580 --> 00:03:07.980
to as the hermit kingdom and that
phrase actually has been attached

00:03:07.980 --> 00:03:09.790
to North Korea today.

00:03:09.790 --> 00:03:18.670 position:56%
The Peninsula itself was a singular
entity until the end of World War 2.

00:03:18.670 --> 00:03:24.580
The Japanese through establishing
treaties, a protectorate

00:03:24.580 --> 00:03:27.890
and then formally annexing
Korea from 1910

00:03:27.890 --> 00:03:33.110
to 1945 were present
on the peninsula.

00:03:33.110 --> 00:03:37.700
At the end of World War
2 they were forced out.

00:03:38.750 --> 00:03:40.610
We see the beginnings
of the Cold War.

00:03:40.610 --> 00:03:45.030
The Soviet Union occupied the
northern half of the country,

00:03:45.030 --> 00:03:49.180
American forces were
stationed in the South.

00:03:50.240 --> 00:03:54.770
Both sides and this was along,
roughly along the 30th parallel

00:03:54.770 --> 00:03:56.990
where the country is divided today.

00:03:56.990 --> 00:04:01.970
Both sides talked about
reunification, they couldn't agree

00:04:01.970 --> 00:04:03.670
on a system of government.

00:04:03.670 --> 00:04:12.060
In 1949, the US and the
USSR withdraw their forces,

00:04:12.060 --> 00:04:15.430
North Korea is arming heavily

00:04:15.430 --> 00:04:20.020
at this time receiving
state-of-the-art technology

00:04:20.020 --> 00:04:22.600
from the Soviet Union.

00:04:22.600 --> 00:04:26.120
South Korea is not
receiving much in the way

00:04:26.120 --> 00:04:28.290
of weapons from the United States.

00:04:28.290 --> 00:04:37.740
In 1950 in June, North Korea
launches a blitzkrieg attack

00:04:37.740 --> 00:04:41.530
into the south and nearly
overruns the country.

00:04:41.530 --> 00:04:51.150
The last line of defense is in
[inaudible] the United Nations led

00:04:51.150 --> 00:04:54.850
by the United States and
Great Britain come to the aid

00:04:54.850 --> 00:05:00.070
of South Korea and turn
the situation around.

00:05:00.070 --> 00:05:04.320
They actually roll back the North
Koreans across the 38th parallel

00:05:04.320 --> 00:05:09.080
and as they close on the Alou
River, the Chinese border,

00:05:09.080 --> 00:05:12.450
the People's Republic
of China enters the war.

00:05:12.450 --> 00:05:20.750
And we have then a situation of
stalemates along the 38th parallel.

00:05:20.750 --> 00:05:26.610
Finally, a cease-fire
is signed, however,

00:05:26.610 --> 00:05:31.350
there is no formal
peace treaty in place.

00:05:31.350 --> 00:05:35.940
The countries are technically
still at war.

00:05:38.570 --> 00:05:44.390
And we see here a map by the
Central Intelligence Agency

00:05:44.390 --> 00:05:47.770
of the DMZ created in 1969.

00:05:47.770 --> 00:05:53.660
This is part of the
geography and map collection.

00:05:53.660 --> 00:06:00.020
Koreans call this Hu Jun sun, the
cease-fire line and it stretches

00:06:00.020 --> 00:06:04.470
across the entire peninsula
150 miles.

00:06:04.470 --> 00:06:08.320
And everywhere along this line

00:06:08.320 --> 00:06:16.900
on both sides are military
installations, artillery, tanks.

00:06:16.900 --> 00:06:20.030 position:56%
They call it the demilitarized zone,

00:06:20.030 --> 00:06:24.770
probably the biggest misnomer
you can apply to the situation.

00:06:24.770 --> 00:06:30.380
It is one of the most
militarized places on earth.

00:06:32.760 --> 00:06:41.310
And if you see the waters to the
left those areas are in dispute

00:06:41.310 --> 00:06:47.250
between the two countries and
there has been live shooting,

00:06:47.250 --> 00:06:53.090
people have died in contesting
where the northern limit is

00:06:53.090 --> 00:06:55.910
of those waters, where
the southern limit is

00:06:55.910 --> 00:06:58.450
of those waters, has
a right to be there.

00:06:58.450 --> 00:07:04.480
I would like to touch a little bit

00:07:04.480 --> 00:07:09.210
about North Korean
geography and place names.

00:07:09.210 --> 00:07:14.970
The North Koreans in sort of
every day common language refer

00:07:14.970 --> 00:07:20.900
to themselves as Choson
referring to the Choson dynasty.

00:07:20.900 --> 00:07:24.780 position:56%
They see South Korea as an extension

00:07:24.780 --> 00:07:31.280
of their country they call it
Nam Choson, Nam meaning south.

00:07:32.950 --> 00:07:37.580
Mind you, South Korea also
has their own place names.

00:07:37.580 --> 00:07:41.180
The common name of Korea Hangul.

00:07:41.180 --> 00:07:44.090
You're referring to North
Korea as an extension

00:07:44.090 --> 00:07:47.970
of their country Phuket
Kong, Phuket meaning north.

00:07:47.970 --> 00:07:52.710
So you would often hear about in
Korean news Nam Phuket relations,

00:07:52.710 --> 00:07:54.210
so north and south.

00:07:54.210 --> 00:08:01.010
The capital city of
North Korea, Pyongyang.

00:08:02.740 --> 00:08:06.230
North Korea shares
borders with China,

00:08:06.230 --> 00:08:11.220
Russia and also South
Korea along the DMZ.

00:08:11.220 --> 00:08:14.530
It's a larger country than
its neighbor in the south,

00:08:14.530 --> 00:08:16.940
neighbor is maybe not
the right word,

00:08:17.970 --> 00:08:21.080
but they're brothers,
it's a house divided.

00:08:24.390 --> 00:08:29.780
The climate of North Korea is hot,
humid summers, very cold winters.

00:08:29.780 --> 00:08:33.240 position:56%
Most of the land is very mountainous
and I'm going to illustrate

00:08:33.240 --> 00:08:35.620
that with some maps
from the division.

00:08:35.620 --> 00:08:39.280
Numerous deep, narrow valleys,
most of the people live

00:08:39.280 --> 00:08:42.460
in valleys on the coastal plains.

00:08:42.460 --> 00:08:47.160
And despite this massive area
of real estate only some 18%

00:08:47.160 --> 00:08:54.760
of that land is arable and
you'll see why with this map.

00:08:54.760 --> 00:08:58.740
This map was drawn in 1944

00:08:58.740 --> 00:09:02.820
by a cartographer named
Richard Eades Harrison.

00:09:02.820 --> 00:09:06.480
He worked for Fortune
Magazine, Time Life Magazine.

00:09:06.480 --> 00:09:10.180
He came into popularity
because he presented cartography

00:09:10.180 --> 00:09:11.480
from a different perspective.

00:09:11.480 --> 00:09:14.570
He said why do we always
show the map top-down,

00:09:14.570 --> 00:09:18.330
show the map that highlights
the information

00:09:18.330 --> 00:09:20.080
that you want the viewer to see.

00:09:20.080 --> 00:09:21.380
So in this map if you look

00:09:21.380 --> 00:09:26.220
at the Korean peninsula you can see
how absolutely mountainous it is,

00:09:26.220 --> 00:09:27.520
in particular North Korea.

00:09:27.520 --> 00:09:33.670
And then you see the coastal
plains where Pyongyang sits.

00:09:33.670 --> 00:09:40.000
And that's where the farming, the
breadbasket of North Korea lies.

00:09:47.040 --> 00:09:51.740
Important to understanding
some of psychology and thinking

00:09:51.740 --> 00:09:54.680
of North Korea, as
well as appreciating

00:09:54.680 --> 00:09:59.950
that of South Korea was
the Japanese occupation.

00:09:59.950 --> 00:10:03.980
They call it the Iljay
Shide [assumed spelling],

00:10:03.980 --> 00:10:07.660
the time of the Japanese Empire.

00:10:07.660 --> 00:10:13.920
Here we have a map of Pyongyang
made by the Japanese in 1921.

00:10:13.920 --> 00:10:17.590
And as you can see, the name
Pyongyang does not appear

00:10:17.590 --> 00:10:19.910
on the map.

00:10:19.910 --> 00:10:25.080
This is the idea of
cultural erasure,

00:10:25.080 --> 00:10:31.380
colonialism where the Japanese
have appropriated the place

00:10:31.380 --> 00:10:33.370
and the name of the place.

00:10:33.370 --> 00:10:40.670
And in the pictures that ring this
map, it's a tourist map by the way,

00:10:40.670 --> 00:10:47.340
in the bottom corner you see a
Mitsubishi factory the Japanese are

00:10:47.340 --> 00:10:51.740
highlighting that we've
modernized the city,

00:10:51.740 --> 00:10:55.110
we are bringing industry
to this peninsula.

00:10:55.110 --> 00:11:00.380
And as you look through the
pictures you see a Buddhist temple,

00:11:00.380 --> 00:11:01.990
an old Korean ship.

00:11:01.990 --> 00:11:05.200
So they're saying well this is the
old way we're the new way and we're

00:11:05.200 --> 00:11:10.740
in harmony with all these
lovely flowers ringing,

00:11:10.740 --> 00:11:12.830
winding through the photographs.

00:11:12.830 --> 00:11:20.750
And there is resentment in
North Korea and South Korea

00:11:20.750 --> 00:11:24.920
to this day about this time period.

00:11:24.920 --> 00:11:30.230
This is a map made by the
North Koreans themselves

00:11:30.230 --> 00:11:33.730
and I chose it precisely because
it has the sort of the same the map

00:11:33.730 --> 00:11:37.800 position:56%
of the city ringed by illustrations.

00:11:37.800 --> 00:11:42.650
This was created for the 13th
international youth festival held

00:11:42.650 --> 00:11:44.360
in 1989.

00:11:44.360 --> 00:11:49.130
This map was actually produced a
year before that in preparation.

00:11:49.130 --> 00:11:53.400
The North Korean government spared
no expense spending a fourth

00:11:53.400 --> 00:11:56.580
of their budget, millions
of dollars,

00:11:56.580 --> 00:11:59.490
to put on a big international show.

00:11:59.490 --> 00:12:05.770
And now we see in the top left
corner there they're highlighting

00:12:05.770 --> 00:12:09.350
their strength as a nation, their
Juche Tower, something I'll talk

00:12:09.350 --> 00:12:10.700
about a little bit later.

00:12:10.700 --> 00:12:14.750
And in the lower right-hand corner
their metro system, which they tout

00:12:14.750 --> 00:12:18.860
as one of the best in the world
and anyone who visits Pyongyang

00:12:18.860 --> 00:12:22.970
and I have not they take
them to these metro centers

00:12:22.970 --> 00:12:28.990
that are very ornate stations
with murals on the walls

00:12:28.990 --> 00:12:31.430 position:56%
and they're very ornately decorated.

00:12:31.430 --> 00:12:37.220
In this map as well like the
other is available to view

00:12:37.220 --> 00:12:41.710
and be researched here at
the Library of Congress.

00:12:43.530 --> 00:12:49.920
The North Korean government is a
hereditary dictatorship supported

00:12:49.920 --> 00:12:51.520
by a single party.

00:12:51.520 --> 00:12:56.920
The Kim family, the Kim
Dynasty has absolute power.

00:12:58.500 --> 00:13:05.560
These titles here in quotes
these are things required

00:13:05.560 --> 00:13:08.240
of the North Korean people to say

00:13:08.240 --> 00:13:10.650
when they reference
one of these leaders.

00:13:10.650 --> 00:13:17.110 position:56%
It is an extreme insult and
probably trouble with the government

00:13:17.110 --> 00:13:22.750
to address one of these
leaders without the title.

00:13:22.750 --> 00:13:26.000
The eternal president, the
eternal general, the marshal.

00:13:32.040 --> 00:13:40.700
Incidentally, Kim Il-sung
was a partisan fighter

00:13:40.700 --> 00:13:49.340
against the Japanese known for
extreme brutality in his tactics

00:13:49.340 --> 00:13:50.850
against the Japanese

00:13:50.850 --> 00:13:55.820
and the Japanese themselves were
a very fierce opponent in war.

00:13:55.820 --> 00:14:04.780
And he idolized Joseph Stalin
in many ways and thought

00:14:04.780 --> 00:14:10.470
to model North Korea
off the Soviet Union,

00:14:10.470 --> 00:14:14.340
but with his own personal spin.

00:14:14.340 --> 00:14:19.740
And that's what we're
talking about here Juche,

00:14:19.740 --> 00:14:24.210
this concept of self-reliance.

00:14:25.830 --> 00:14:28.330
This ideology is very hard

00:14:28.330 --> 00:14:32.970
to explain what I'm telling you
here is a very distilled simplified

00:14:32.970 --> 00:14:36.460
version, but it's a
mixture of communism,

00:14:36.460 --> 00:14:40.160
nationalism and Confucianism.

00:14:40.160 --> 00:14:46.350
The leadership holds a place that's
nearly religious in the country.

00:14:46.350 --> 00:14:54.690
And they are governing
24.7 million people,

00:14:54.690 --> 00:14:59.320
in the South 48.9 million people.

00:14:59.320 --> 00:15:02.060
They have a greater area in
the north, smaller population.

00:15:02.060 --> 00:15:10.820 position:56%
They tout the fact that they provide
healthcare, education, housing,

00:15:10.820 --> 00:15:17.170
food, etcetera for their
population with a caveat.

00:15:17.170 --> 00:15:25.620
The quality of life depends
on a person's loyalty ranking.

00:15:25.620 --> 00:15:31.290 position:56%
North Korea begins a file on anyone
over the age of 17 you're classified

00:15:31.290 --> 00:15:35.670
as loyal to the regime,
wavering to the regime

00:15:35.670 --> 00:15:38.710
or on the outs with the regime.

00:15:38.710 --> 00:15:43.110
And if you're on the outs with the
regime almost three generations it

00:15:43.110 --> 00:15:47.330
takes to be rehabilitated to
be brought back into the fold.

00:15:47.330 --> 00:15:51.750
So if someone commits an
offense they, their children

00:15:51.750 --> 00:15:54.880
and their children's
children are ostracized.

00:15:54.880 --> 00:15:59.000
And this is a political
cast system known

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:02.800
as sung-boon meaning constituents.

00:16:02.800 --> 00:16:10.150
And as we know, for many defectors
North Korea there's limited civil

00:16:10.150 --> 00:16:15.770
liberties, state-controlled
press and internet.

00:16:15.770 --> 00:16:19.640
There is restrictions on
travel to and from North Korea.

00:16:19.640 --> 00:16:23.680
Our guests, Mr. Melvin, he
can't visit North Korean

00:16:23.680 --> 00:16:31.030
as you can imagine he's revealing
too much information about them.

00:16:31.030 --> 00:16:36.280
A great tragedy is happening in
North Korea is chronic shortages

00:16:36.280 --> 00:16:39.970
of food, energy and medicine.

00:16:39.970 --> 00:16:46.360
And this coincides with
the end of the Soviet Union

00:16:46.360 --> 00:16:49.740
who are bankrolling the
North Koreans in many ways

00:16:49.740 --> 00:16:52.610
like they were bankrolling the
Cubans and the East Germans

00:16:52.610 --> 00:16:54.920
and all these other countries.

00:16:54.920 --> 00:16:57.010
This cash flow has stopped.

00:16:57.010 --> 00:17:02.580
And the North Korean priorities,
which I'll get to in a minute,

00:17:02.580 --> 00:17:06.860
are military not treating
their people.

00:17:06.860 --> 00:17:10.020
And so they're relying on foreign
aid and has gone back and forth

00:17:10.020 --> 00:17:15.260 position:56%
where the United Nations, the United
States, South Korea is sending food

00:17:15.260 --> 00:17:18.080
and medicine to them and
they're turning around

00:17:18.080 --> 00:17:20.270 position:56%
and they're still arming themselves.

00:17:20.270 --> 00:17:30.690
And that has to do with this
second ideology of North Korea.

00:17:30.690 --> 00:17:36.670
Sun-goon army first, sun from the
Chinese character primary first,

00:17:36.670 --> 00:17:39.700
goon as Yuk goon army, military.

00:17:39.700 --> 00:17:42.420
It's like a modern day Sparta.

00:17:42.420 --> 00:17:48.040
They have the world's
fourth largest military

00:17:48.040 --> 00:17:50.610 position:56%
and while they have dated technology

00:17:50.610 --> 00:17:56.170
in the right hands
it's very lethal stuff.

00:17:56.170 --> 00:17:59.950
And most of their equipment would
have been considered modern during

00:17:59.950 --> 00:18:05.570
the Vietnam era, that's the highest
level of technology they have

00:18:05.570 --> 00:18:11.560
in terms of fighters and
tanks dating back to the 70's.

00:18:11.560 --> 00:18:14.920
Why does it stop there because the
Russians are no longer sending them

00:18:14.920 --> 00:18:16.800
the latest stuff?

00:18:16.800 --> 00:18:19.360
And this we'll get to our last
point here before we bring

00:18:19.360 --> 00:18:23.910 position:56%
up Mr. Melvin about nuclear weapons.

00:18:23.910 --> 00:18:26.410
They're spending an
outrageously high amount

00:18:26.410 --> 00:18:32.100
of money on defense 8.2 billion.

00:18:32.100 --> 00:18:41.150
They have an active military
of 1.1 million people.

00:18:41.150 --> 00:18:48.010
Ten years of mandatory
service in the military,

00:18:48.010 --> 00:18:53.920
it's an incredibly long period
of time to have the young men

00:18:53.920 --> 00:18:59.780
of your nation to committed
to military service instead

00:18:59.780 --> 00:19:01.080
of developing their minds

00:19:01.080 --> 00:19:03.570
and developing the
economy of the nation.

00:19:03.570 --> 00:19:10.410
They are preoccupied with training
for war and they use incidentally

00:19:10.410 --> 00:19:13.460
for pet projects of
the regime to build,

00:19:13.460 --> 00:19:17.710
to act as construction workers,
to help in harvest time.

00:19:17.710 --> 00:19:25.380 position:56%
And their special forces, which is
numbers around some 200,000 soldiers

00:19:25.380 --> 00:19:28.650
and I don't want to say men
because women are under arms

00:19:28.650 --> 00:19:33.600
in North Korea too, it's
15 years of service.

00:19:33.600 --> 00:19:38.280
That's an incredibly long
period of time as well.

00:19:38.280 --> 00:19:47.630
This contrasts with South Korea
some 655,000 soldiers and depending

00:19:47.630 --> 00:19:52.110
on the branch of service
22 to 24 months.

00:19:52.110 --> 00:19:59.130
There's two different
mentalities towards defense

00:19:59.130 --> 00:20:02.790
and defense preparation
as you can see.

00:20:02.790 --> 00:20:05.550
Total militarized population

00:20:05.550 --> 00:20:11.310
of North Korea is an
astounding 7.6 million people.

00:20:11.310 --> 00:20:17.430
You remember we said there's
24 some million people living

00:20:17.430 --> 00:20:18.730
in North Korea.

00:20:18.730 --> 00:20:22.450
Close to a third of their
people are under arms.

00:20:22.450 --> 00:20:32.350
The capital of South Korea Seoul
is in a precarious position,

00:20:32.350 --> 00:20:41.090
it's not far some 30 some miles
from the DMZ and it is in range

00:20:41.090 --> 00:20:43.330
of North Korean artillery.

00:20:43.330 --> 00:20:48.760
It's projected that there's
some 13,000 artillery pieces

00:20:48.760 --> 00:20:55.060
in that sector of the DMZ that are
