administrative data we've published

00:38:41.420 --> 00:38:46.890
it as the 38 North Digital Atlas
that's on our webpage, 38north.org.

00:38:46.890 --> 00:38:51.060
And then the infrastructure
mapping we're trying to move

00:38:51.060 --> 00:38:57.080
to a web-based system so that
researchers can use it more easily.

00:38:57.080 --> 00:39:00.970
And it's such an enormous
and complex file,

00:39:00.970 --> 00:39:04.870
it's taking a long
time to get this done.

00:39:04.870 --> 00:39:10.090
But the end goal is to
build a web-based platform

00:39:10.090 --> 00:39:13.690
where everybody can access this
data and to have a team of people

00:39:13.690 --> 00:39:18.010
who are constantly monitoring
our various sources for updates

00:39:18.010 --> 00:39:22.740
of that information and so
that it can always be updated

00:39:22.740 --> 00:39:27.590
and made available to the public.

00:39:27.590 --> 00:39:30.800
Why is this important, well
by combining satellite imagery

00:39:30.800 --> 00:39:36.260
with the largest non-classified
database we can more easily monitor

00:39:36.260 --> 00:39:39.240
changes across the country
and get a better sense

00:39:39.240 --> 00:39:41.060
of what's happening there.

00:39:41.060 --> 00:39:47.540 position:56%
And to communicate these findings
to various North Korea stakeholders.

00:39:48.840 --> 00:39:56.360
So information sources, this is a
lot of research and verification.

00:39:56.360 --> 00:40:00.450
I lean very heavily on North
Korea's efficient, they're helpful

00:40:00.450 --> 00:40:02.110
and they each have
their own drawbacks.

00:40:02.110 --> 00:40:06.440
So official publications,
North Korean television KCTV,

00:40:06.440 --> 00:40:12.340
Naenara is a North Korean web
portal it's updated every day.

00:40:12.340 --> 00:40:18.100
Uriminzokkiri is a North Korean
organization that targets contents

00:40:18.100 --> 00:40:25.780 position:56%
to overseas Koreans and Choson Sinbo
is run by Koreans who are loyal

00:40:25.780 --> 00:40:32.040
to North Korean who live in Japan.

00:40:32.040 --> 00:40:37.120
Any books and software that the
North Koreans publish the Library

00:40:37.120 --> 00:40:40.900
of Congress has a tremendous
collection of these items

00:40:40.900 --> 00:40:45.180
as does the Seoul National
Library in South Korea.

00:40:45.180 --> 00:40:50.370
Although the Library of Congress
ones are easier to access.

00:40:50.370 --> 00:40:56.500
The drawbacks for these official
publications, you get a wealth

00:40:56.500 --> 00:40:59.430
of information, you probably
get the most timely information

00:40:59.430 --> 00:41:00.850
if a new factory has been built

00:41:00.850 --> 00:41:05.640
or something has changed names
you're most likely only going

00:41:05.640 --> 00:41:07.570
to find out about it through
official publications.

00:41:07.570 --> 00:41:16.160
But these only cover places that
the North Korean government wants

00:41:16.160 --> 00:41:17.460
to highlight.

00:41:17.460 --> 00:41:20.150
So if you're interested
in, you know,

00:41:20.150 --> 00:41:27.920
developments at a military site or
a prison camp they're never going

00:41:27.920 --> 00:41:31.440
to be updated on the North
Korean official publications,

00:41:31.440 --> 00:41:34.640
you can only get information
about that from satellite imagery

00:41:34.640 --> 00:41:37.070
or from interviewing defectors.

00:41:37.070 --> 00:41:42.350
Declassified documents are
really helpful, you know,

00:41:42.350 --> 00:41:45.850
the intelligence community has
been researching a lot of places

00:41:45.850 --> 00:41:47.210
in North Korea for decades.

00:41:47.210 --> 00:41:53.640
You can get declassified documents
on North Korea up till the 1980's,

00:41:53.640 --> 00:41:56.520
I think I haven't seen
anything from the 90's yet.

00:41:56.520 --> 00:42:02.020
And these are really helpful,
they generally have maps

00:42:02.020 --> 00:42:05.400
and some old satellite
images in them.

00:42:05.400 --> 00:42:11.600
They have a lot of coordinates
which still work if you want

00:42:11.600 --> 00:42:14.010
to copy those coordinates
into Google Earth.

00:42:14.010 --> 00:42:17.450
The problem with declassified
documents is

00:42:17.450 --> 00:42:19.970
in this case you're
getting they're very old,

00:42:19.970 --> 00:42:22.740
so the 1980's is a long
time ago in North Korea.

00:42:22.740 --> 00:42:25.270
Even North Korea has changed
significantly since then.

00:42:25.270 --> 00:42:31.140
There are also sort
of targets things

00:42:31.140 --> 00:42:33.730
that we might be interested
in blowing up one day.

00:42:33.730 --> 00:42:38.000
So if you're interested
in a new paper factory

00:42:38.000 --> 00:42:43.140
or fishing station it's
probably not going to be in them.

00:42:43.140 --> 00:42:48.780
The other thing that's frustrating
is the declassified documents refer

00:42:48.780 --> 00:42:53.810
to the places -- generally refer
to the places they've identified

00:42:53.810 --> 00:42:57.460
by what the intelligence community
calls them or what they used

00:42:57.460 --> 00:43:00.820
to be called not what the North
Koreans actually call them.

00:43:00.820 --> 00:43:04.460
And so there are a
number of times I found

00:43:04.460 --> 00:43:08.990
out where I would identify a
factory from a North Korean source

00:43:08.990 --> 00:43:14.490 position:56%
and describe a name to it and then I
would see a name that was unfamiliar

00:43:14.490 --> 00:43:17.310
in a declassified document and
I would punch in the coordinates

00:43:17.310 --> 00:43:19.540
and find out that they were
the same thing it's just

00:43:19.540 --> 00:43:25.080
that the intelligence community
had a different name for this place

00:43:25.080 --> 00:43:26.580
than the North Koreans did.

00:43:26.580 --> 00:43:31.690
And so as far as I know I'm the
only one who is in the business

00:43:31.690 --> 00:43:34.510
of putting this data together.

